metadata.name: Smoke #97
metadata.description:
Inspired by the hot weather of the city.
Made in August 2022, Milano, Italy.

5 visible Features:
-Mood: tender, bleed, icecream, summer in Milano, evening, futurepunk, acid, love
-Size: small, regular, big
-Density: low, moderate, high, very high
-Speed: slow, moderate, fast
-Emissions: from 2 to 9

Some of the features are very rare, others less, some more common.

The design is being optimized to render at different speeds depending on the size of the window. The smaller the size, the faster the render and lower the detail, viceversa bigger the size, slower the render and higher the detail.
The moire effect of lines that are making the shades of the artwork will look thick with a low resolution, and become finer and more detailed the higher the resolution. You can use this feature to create quick previews or to save very Hi-Resolution images.
To save an image with the size of the window press S once the image is fully rendered.
The fx(hash) thumbnail is saved at 1425px x 1900px.
To save a Hi-Resolution image 3000px x 4000px press H and wait, the page will reload and start to render. Please be patient.

Built using p5js, published under CC-BY-NC-4.0 license.

Once the collection will be fully minted, the variations button will be disabled.

metadata.name: Julia's Magical Bulbs - 3rd 4th 5th Powers #21
metadata.description:
Julia's Magical Bulbs are 3D dimensional fractals, based on the Julia Sets of the Mandelbulb fractal.  In this edition we explore the 3rd, 4th and 5th powers.

The token is interactive, use your mouse-wheel to zoom-in and see all the little details. You will find a menu in the lower-right corner which allows you to play with the iterations and camera position. You can also render high-resolution images here.

A little bit of magic happens when you select low iteration values, perhaps your token will even default to this.

Technical:

Not all browsers support multi-threaded modules, the fallback mode is quite slow. Try Chrome if your browser is not supported.

Calculated in full 64-bit on the CPU (not the GPU) for more accurate and detailed images.

metadata.name: blub blub #79
metadata.description:
blub blub is an exploration of form.

We begin with two simple shapes, one defining the shape that will be drawn, the other defining the path along which it will traverse.

Each shape is then paired with a sinusoid that either modifies the size of the shape that is drawn, or the offset from the path it is traversing.

This simple set of rules leads to a surprising large variety of forms.

metadata.name: Stippled Sketch #131
metadata.description:
Stippled Sketch is an experimental attempt to imitate the result of sitting down and mindlessly finding form on the page. The process of pressing the pen to paper in a rhythmic, repeated pattern can be a form of meditation, much like doodling. 

The form at the center of the sketch can sometimes take a clear and recognizable shape, but it can also appear meandering and meaningless at times. Some forms appear more often than others (such as a clover and circle), but the equation at the core of the algorithm has surprised me quite a few times with unique and unusual shapes, even after reviewing thousands of previews. 

I like to think of this collection as a reflection of a time in my life when I wanted to say so much—and I could put the pen to the paper, but I knew that no words would have any effect, so I sketched to focus my attention on something else instead. 

— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — 
Special thanks to Laurent Houdard and Lisa Orth for helping with a few technical aspects.

metadata.name: Boom_fx_max #196
metadata.description:
Boom_fx_max, by Stephen Boyd  
August, 2022  
Little India, Toronto, Canada.

This is a free mint for anyone who is a holder of Boom_fx as of August 31, 2022, 00:11:00Z. 

Signed 18" x 12" or 12" x 12" prints are available to holders for both Boom_fx and Boom_fx_max tokens on request. Please send a DM for more information.

Any unclaimed reserves will be released after four days and available at a price to be determined. 


Project Description
---
Boom_fx_max uses all eleven days of data in one image. This constitutes 4,567 earthquakes being represented in every output. This differs from the original Boom_fx which used hours of time on one of the eleven days and typically included a few hundred seismic events.

There are eleven new colour palettes and seven different ratios to organize relationships between visual elements.

The earthquake data comes from the USGS API. There is further documentation (./documentation/Information_about_boom_fx_max.md) included with this project that outlines how this data was collected and the information included in these feeds.


Three Features
---
1. Aspect ratios:
   - Landscape
   - Portrait
   - Square
2. Eleven colour palettes
3. Seven Organizing Principle Ratios:
   - Super Golden Ratio
   - PHI
   - Golden Angle
   - Silver Ratio
   - Euler's Number
   - Reciprocal Fibonacci Constant
   - Feigenbaum Constant


Interaction
---
Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press t: thumbnail @ a maximum pixel width or height of 200px
- Press s: your current screen size
- Press p: print size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 4800px which is 16"@300dpi
- Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ a maximum pixel width or height of 2160px
- Press m: Max size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 10800px.

The filename will include some metadata such as the unique hash, date and time at time of capture.


Appreciation
---
Thank you to everyone who has collected one my pieces.

Thank you to the USGS for making this data available.

And thank you the most to KIRH.


Data Sources, Software Libraries and VCS / Source Code
--- 
Data Sources
All earthquake data is sourced from the USGS Earthquake API for the International Federation of Digital Seismograph Networks (FDSN). 

Software Libraries Used
Made with Processing / P5.js  
p5.js v1.4.1 February 02, 2022
